Description
When a murderer kills, what do they choose to do in the minutes, hours and days after their crime?

Hotelier Bei Carter was found dead in her Bridlington guest house by her husband Terry. With only three guests at the hotel, two of whom were accounted for at the time of the murder, police attention turned to John Heald, who had just checked in to the B&B. After Bei’s murder, John Heald went on the run for seven days, making his way back to his native South Yorkshire, where several public sightings had been reported to the police. However, after evading police capture by lying low in woodland near Rotherham, John surfaced at a nearby café where the owner recognised him and reported him to the police, who arrested him soon after. Police discovered that killer John was already on the run from police in South Yorkshire after he faced rape charges. During the court hearing, John Heald admitted to Bei’s murder but stated it was not deliberate or pre-meditated. However, before he could be sentenced John hanged himself in his cell.

The Employment Rights Bill had its Second Reading in the House of Lords. It is one of the Government’s flagship Bills and proposes widespread reform to employment law. 

Yet is also a Bill with significant detail yet to be worked out. At second reading, Lord Hunt of Wirral highlighted the scale of this challenge: the Bill contains 11 Henry VIII powers and 173 delegated powers. 

As the Lords begin their scrutiny of the Bill, Director of Legislative Affairs in our Public Law & Policy team, Nikki Da Costa, and Employment Partner Stefan Martin, consider the latest developments across zero hours contracts, day one rights, and collective redundancy and share advice on how you can engage with and shape the Bill.

More than 130 cardinals from across the world have gathered in the Vatican to begin the process of electing a new pontiff following the death of Pope Francis.
 
They will walk to the Sistine Chapel this afternoon to cast their votes beneath the famous Renaissance frescoes.
 
Once cardinals enter the chapel, around 17:30 local time (16:30 BST), the conclave begins and they will have no communication with the outside world until a new Pope is elected. 
 
After the first vote later today, smoke will emerge from the Sistine Chapel chimney – black smoke means more voting will take place tomorrow, white means there’s a new pope.

Welcome to our latest UK General Election prediction video for April 2022.

Under the fixed term parliaments act the next UK general election is due to be held on 2nd May 2024 but with repeal of the TFPA likely in the coming months the election may well be held before 2nd May 2024!

Whenever the election is held we will be releasing a video every month charting changing public opinion through reliable, BPC (British Polling Council) registered national and international opinion pollsters such as YouGov, MORI, Survation, DeltaPoll, Opinium and more....

Based on multiple polls conducted during March 2022 the April 2022 UK general election prediction from Electoral Calculus is for Labour to be short of an overall majority by 24 seats - So a hung parliament is still favoured for the next UK general election but with Labour probably close enough to govern either as a minority administration or with other parties in a coalition of some other arrangement.

This video also include a prediction for the local council election to be held on Thursday 5th May 2022.

As we move closer to the next UK general election we will be charting how opinion changes for the main political parties and the party leaders.

In this video, we dive into the UK's growing political instability and explore what’s coming next. With five Prime Ministers in just over six years and public trust in government at a record low, the UK’s political crisis is escalating. We examine the fragmented political leadership that has created chaos in Westminster, leaving the nation’s government paralyzed and unable to tackle key issues like healthcare, defense, and the cost-of-living crisis. 

The impact of Brexit continues to haunt the UK, creating confusion, economic challenges, and deepening divisions, especially in regions like Scotland and Northern Ireland. Meanwhile, regional independence movements are gaining traction, with Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland pushing for more autonomy. 

The rise of populist movements is adding fuel to the fire, promising radical change while amplifying division and distrust. We also look at how media polarization and misinformation are distorting the political narrative, making it harder for the public to discern the truth. 

On the global stage, the UK is grappling with geopolitical pressures, and its internal instability is weakening its international influence. As these issues intensify, the future of the UK's political system hangs in the balance.

 Watch this video for a deeper understanding of the crisis and what could happen next. Subscribe for more updates!

Join us as we explore why freedom of speech is not just a constitutional right but a cornerstone of democracy.

How do we measure freedom of speech, and what does it mean to be aligned with allies who may not share our unwavering commitment to this principle?

Our conversation takes a closer look at JD Vance, a prominent political figure, and his recent speech addressing the state of freedom of speech in America. Vance’s insights highlight the precarious position of this liberty in our society today. Are we on the brink of losing our cherished freedom of expression? We discuss the potential implications of diminishing speech rights and what that could mean for the future of democracy in America.

To foster a better understanding of these complex issues, we also consider how aligning our moral values with our allies could strengthen international relationships. What role does freedom of speech play in this alignment, and how can we promote a shared commitment to this vital principle?

text:
The Next Morning is a short film by Olivier Award-winning writer James Graham, commissioned to mark the 80th anniversary of the end of the Second World War.

Directed by Alice Wordsworth and produced by Emma Hall, this original film confronts the lingering echoes of war through the eyes of two generations, asking what the end of the Second World War means in a world shaped by its aftermath. 

Set in contemporary Britain, the film interweaves three stories of children uncovering personal reflections from the day peace was declared in Europe in 1945.

As a wartime time capsule is uncovered in an allotment, a granddaughter discovers a diary in the attic, and a grandson reads an unsent letter to a father lost in the war, memories of VE Day resonate with new meaning. A new generation listens, reads, and remembers as the echoes of history come alive through diaries, keepsakes, and family stories — culminating in a new time capsule buried for the future.

Combining archival footage with deeply personal monologues, the film is a celebration of remembrance, resilience, and renewal — reminding us that peace is a legacy we must choose to carry forward. 

The film is part of a year-long schools engagement programme responding to the events of VE and VJ Day and this significant period of the UK’s history. 

Starting in September 2025, the schools engagement programme for Key Stages 3 and 4 will be delivered as part of a nationwide tour of Dear England, which will take the Olivier-winning play to 16 venues across the UK.  

The schools programme will encourage young people across the UK to reflect on their own place in history, with assemblies and workshops delivered in schools across England, supporting students to share the hopes and aspirations that they have for themselves and other young people 80 years’ from now.  

A resulting sound archive will form a 2025-2026 time capsule containing young people's voices for now, and the future. 

The Next Morning is made possible thanks to funding from the Department for Culture, Media and Sport.

text:
Football isn't coming home for England and the hopes of an extra bank holiday have been dashed. Prime Minister Sir Keir Starmer had been asked by Gary Neville on ITV on Sunday if there would be a bank holiday to mark England's success.

At the time, Gary Neville said: "60 million people are all asking the same question - are they getting a day off? Are they getting a bank holiday? It's on you." The Prime Minister replied: "I don't know about that. Let's get through the next few hours. Let's get their hands on that trophy. We need to mark it in some way but we'll have to see what that is...an appropriate way."

However, it was not meant to be as England lost to Spain 2-1 at the Olympiastadion in Berlin. This means the next bank holiday will be Monday, August 26. Two extra one-off bank holidays were held across the UK in 2022, one for the Queen's platinum jubilee and another for her funeral.

text:
Panel: Using apps, devices and UX to deepen engagement

Speakers
Alejandro Casal, KPN
Anette Schaefer, EIT Culture & Creativity
Chris Van Der Linden, Liberty Global
Simon James, Synamedia
Roland Sars, Media Distillery
Brigita Brjuhhanov, Elisa

Description
We are interested in how app, device and UX strategies can help operators and streaming services reach more consumers and then engage them more deeply. We consider the market impact when viewers can choose from set-top boxes, operator-developed Smart TVs and operator apps on Smart TVs or retail set-top boxes (like Apple TV) – does CPE diversity mean more touchpoints and price points and broaden the market for subscription and free TV? This panel explores how we deepen engagement with all TV viewers and where appropriate, how extra engagement can be monetised. We want to know the potential for emerging concepts like immersive storytelling, interactive overlays (especially in sport), personalized highlights packages, next-gen accessibility, etc. There is a special focus on next steps in content discovery, plus the potential for AI to improve UX personalisation.
title: Apps, Devices & UX to Deepen TV Engagement | KPN, Synamedia, Liberty Global, Elisa, Synamedia
